SI 370 - Homework #2: Data Visualization¶

Background¶

This homework assignment focuses on the visual analysis of the COVID-19 data avaiable here: https://covid19datahub.io/articles/api/python.html. A description of the dataset can be found at https://covid19datahub.io/articles/doc/data.html

Your main task in this assignment is to explore the data using the data manipulation, analysis, and visualization methods we covered in class as well as those in the assigned readings. You may need to consult pandas and seaborn documentation, as well as Stack Overflow, or other online resources.

Total Points and Rubric¶

Each question is worth 10 points. Points will be allocated according to the following rubric:

  • 90-100%: Question is correctly and completely answered. Answer consists of well-written code that conforms to PEP 8 guidelines and is accompanied by a written interpretation in a Markdown block. Written interpretation does not contain spelling, grammar or stylistic errors (see https://faculty.washington.edu/heagerty/Courses/b572/public/StrunkWhite.pdf for a detailed specifications). Minor problems, such as formatting, incorrect submissions, missing names, etc. will result in less than 100%.
  • 75-85% : Answer is mostly complete and correct; two or fewer noticeable omissions or errors. Minor stylistic flaws, either in code or in written interpretation.
  • 50-70%: Answer has significant omissions or errors; Noticeable departure from PEP-8 guildelines and/or moderate spelling, grammar, or style issues in written interpretations.
  • 25-45%: Question is perfunctorily attempted. Substantial parts are missing or incorrect.
  • 0 points: Question not attempted.

I wanted to analyze if information campaigns played an affect on vaccine distributed. Initially when we did not know very much about COVID there was no vaccines or campaigns. As we continue to analyze, we can see that when covid started getting bad around 2021-01 areas who had coordinated public information given recieved more vaccines than those in areas where people just urged about COVID or did nothing at all. At the end of the graph you can start to see the affect these campaigns had dwindle down a little as the rates for urging and coordinating start to become more similar. Interstingly at the end there is a huge spike, much larger than the other categories, in when public officials simply urge.

In these two graphs I wanted to first narrow down on US data. The policy I chose to look at was the one regarding gatherings. In the first graph I compared the deaths to confirmed cases ratios during all of the phases of restricted gatherings. Here we can see there is not a trend showing that stricter polices lead to less deaths. To further analyze this I created a second graph showing the death to overall population ratios. Interesting the tighest resriction is shown to have the highest ratio. Disclaimer These two sets are not enough to come to any overarching conclusions regarding the effectivenss of these restrictions because of other factors that can affect rates, ratios, and data as a whole as well.
